{
  "text": "One clue to the function of the postmitotic response may be that prolonged activation of the mitotic checkpoint has been causally implicated in tumorigenesis [CITATION_1] . Indeed, mitosis is frequently prolonged in cancer cells, and several genetic and epigenetic defects, which cause mitotic arrest, can contribute to cancer [CITATION_2] . For some of these defects, such as inactivation of Rb and hCDC4, oncogenic activation of c-Myc, and the presence of supernumerary chromosomes and/or centrosomes, prolonged mitosis is one of many cellular effects, which may or may not be oncogenic [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . However, mitotic arrest and cancer also develop in mice overexpressing Mad2, a protein principally involved in mitotic checkpoint signaling, providing strong evidence that prolonged mitotic checkpoint activation can directly promote tumorigenesis [CITATION_7] . Accordingly, the p53-dependent postmitotic response may serve to inhibit the propagation of cells, which acquire oncogenic properties during prolonged activation of the mitotic checkpoint.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "21352214",
    "[CITATION_2]": "21352214",
